\begin_layout Standard
Across the board, the standard deviations relative to the means are high,
 due to the spread of the data and the fact that some states rarely occur,
 i.e.
 have few data points (shown on plots below).
 The mean and median agree on their predictions, although they produce a
 different ranking (labelling) for each actor/sentiment type, as seen in
 the table.
 Because those labels are not conclusive, I use the MCDM R package to identify
 the optimal ranking based on several different methods for computing multi-crit
eria decisions [Ceballos Martin].
 This ranking is based on maximizing positive emotion percent and minimizing
 negative emotion percent (i.e.
 the choice ranked first is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 willing to negotiate state).
 As it turns out, all of the methods rank the latent states in the same
 way: states 
\begin_inset Formula $1,2,3$
\end_inset

 map to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (conciliatory), 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

moderate,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (hardline).
 This result is robust to changing the measure of central tendency (i.e.
 median or mean) used in the decision matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Markov transition matrices shown below, respectively, represent the
 probabilities of regime switching for FARC and the government, estimated
 using the negative and positive emotion measures and labeled according
 to the results of the decision matrix.
 The values in the diagonals reflect the persistence of some states.
 For instance, when FARC is hardline, there is a high probability that it
 will continue to be hardline.
\end_layout

