\begin_layout Standard
The graphs below show the estimated state of FARC and the government, respective
ly, over the time period of the negotiations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename hmm_farc.eps
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename hmm_govt.eps
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These graphs indicate a number of surprising results: First and foremost,
 it appears that FARC's willingness to negotiate has usually been medium
 to high.
 The government's willingness, however, seems more volatile, with a high
 level of regime switching especially during 2013 and 2015.
 Interestingly, the government tends to shift from low to high and rarely
 was in the moderate state, with the exception of a period from mid-2014
 to mid-2015, during which FARC was also in a moderate state.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The irregularity and frequency of data (statements may be issued days, weeks,
 or months apart) explains some of this volatility.
 There are three times as many government documents than FARC documents,
 and government statements are issued more frequently.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One likely cause of the government's volatile transitions is that its statements
 must address many different audiences and groups: toward FARC, the government
 must be a tough negotiator; for domestic critics, the government must appease
 hawks' concerns about specific provisions such as seats in the legislature
 for ex-guerrillas or amnesty from prosecution; for the military, the government
 must reassure them of their place in the conflict and about concerns regarding
 potential prosecution of military personnel for acts committed during the
 war; for the international community, the government must pledge its commitment
 to peace as it possibly seeks regional or United Nations assistance with
 the implementation of any deal; and for the public, the government must
 convince them that an agreement will actually bring about peace, that the
 voices of victims of the conflict have been heard, and that they should
 vote in favor of the agreement if it is on a referendum.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The House of Representatives passed a bill in 2013 requiring that any deal
 from Havana must survive a referendum, but this was followed by wrangling
 in the constitutional court and various statements by the president suggesting
 that a popular vote would happen if an agreement was made but that this
 was not legally required.[El Tiempo] 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, anecdotally we may consider some events in the peace timeline that
 are objectively likely to have affected whether the government was in a
 hardline or conciliatory state.
 In June 2015, FARC launched a series of attacks including attacking police
 stations and bombing infrastructure such as oil pipelines in Norte de Santander
, Putumayo, and Nariño, resulting in an oil spill that caused severe environment
al damage and contaminated the water supply of thousands; and bombing power
 stations that supplied electricity to the cities of Buenaventura and Tumaco.
 [Guardian] [Colombia Peace Timeline] [Colombia Reports] This time period
 coincides with the high level of regime-switching observed in the government
 graph.
 Also interesting, however, is the lack of regime switching in November
 2014 following FARC's kidnapping of a general.
 The government suspended peace talks from November 16 and talks resumed
 on December 9
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Although threatening to suspend or suspending talks (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

walking away from the table
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) may seem like a common bluffing maneuver, it occurred very rarely during
 these negotiations.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 after the general was returned; however, this entire episode falls within
 the government's long spell in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

moderate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 willingness to negotiate state.
 [Colombia Peace Timeline]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly, with noisy and irregular data, matching events to states is imperfect
 and in any event assumes certain associations between events and sentiment
 measures (e.g.
 in the paragraph above, I assume that devastating FARC attacks are associated
 with more negative sentiment and a less conciliatory stance from the government
).
 More generally, although sentiment and regime changes may be very sensitive
 to events, the broader implication of this model is that neither side spends
 much time of the negotiations in the state of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 willingness.
 Moreover, although skepticism has been a common response to FARC's claim
 that it is committed to negotiating (rather than the violent means the
 organization has avowed) and its apparent willingness to accede (in provisional
 topic-specific agreements) to terms that fall short of its Marxist ideology,
 this model shows that FARC in fact was usually moderately to highly willing
 to negotiate over this time period.
 This conclusion is borne out by the (out-of-sample) peace agreement reached
 just three months after documents were scraped for this project.
 Using sentiment as a rough metric of FARC's true level of engagement in
 the talks is a new measure for use in war and peace studies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These probabilities also provide insight into whether states are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sticky
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and may shed light on the lasting impact of events such as violent attacks
 during negotiations.
 If a FARC attack prompts a government hardline response, is this state
 persistent over time? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph*
Sentiment response results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the second part of this paper, I estimate the responsiveness of sentiment
 to sentiment, in the form of a Markov transition matrix.
 As discussed previously, the probabilities in this matrix are calculated
 using a multinomial logit with maximum likelihood estimation.
 I test four models: The first is a simple MNL of 
\begin_inset Formula $State_{t+1}$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $State_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Model (2) adds year indicators to control for year effects, because of
 potential associations between sentiment and time (e.g.
 one might argue that sentiment in later years should be higher than sentiment
 in earlier years because of the survival of the peace negotiations).
 Model (3) adds covariates for violence and public opinion to the base model,
 in the form of log transformed number of FARC actions recorded in that
 month and log transformed presidential approval ratings for that month.
 Model (4) includes both the year indicators and the violence and public
 opinion covariates.
 Thus, Model (1) is nested in all of the other models, and Models (2) and
 (3) are nested in Model (4).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

