\begin_layout Standard
Does sentiment respond to sentiment? There is a 
\begin_inset Formula $0.01$
\end_inset

 probability that the response to a low-sentiment government statement will
 be a low-sentiment statement from FARC, versus a 
\begin_inset Formula $0.14$
\end_inset

 probability that the response will be a high-sentiment FARC statement.
 On the other hand, there is a 
\begin_inset Formula $0.17$
\end_inset

 probability that the response to a high-sentiment government statement
 is a high-sentiment FARC statement, compared with a 
\begin_inset Formula $0.01$
\end_inset

 probability that it will be a low-sentiment FARC statement.
 (Another government statement is most likely to follow a government statement,
 for either level of sentiment.) This result seems promising: FARC seems
 more likely to respond to government statements with high positive sentiment.
 The government, on the other hand, is equally likely 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.08)$
\end_inset

 to respond with either level of sentiment to a low-sentiment FARC statement.
 Interestingly, the government is more likely 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.32)$
\end_inset

 to respond with a low-sentiment statement to a high-sentiment FARC statement
 and less likely to respond with a high-sentiment statement 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.23)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transition matrix provides a new method for answering some other questions
 about negotiations.
 We might ask whether sentiment is persistent or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sticky
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

; and whether, for instance, a shock such as a terrorist attack might permanentl
y derail sentiment (and the peace process).
 Low government sentiment has a high probability 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.73)$
\end_inset

 of continuing in subsequent time periods, although it should be noted that
 this was also the most common state occurring in the data.
 High government sentiment is about as likely to persist 
\begin_inset Formula $(0.49)$
\end_inset

 than it is to be followed by any of the other states combined.
 FARC's persistence is lower, with 
\begin_inset Formula $0.33$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0.40$
\end_inset

 for low and high sentiment, respectively, although this result may partly
 reflect the relatively fewer FARC statements in the dataset.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph*
Validation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Up until now the estimation has not used the jointly issued statements.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper is a first attempt at applying some text and sentiment analysis
 methods from psychology to the study of conflict negotiations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overview of estimation and results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Limitations of current project:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Validate HMM labels using k-means or other form of validation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Custom dictionary instead of LIWC
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further research:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Refine/adapt sentiment analysis for political science 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Answer questions about types of violence (need disaggregated data) as peace
 process spoilers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use new data to reassess question once FARC agreement is reached
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Apply to other conflicts if data is available
\end_layout

